<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=164&amp;p=1052#p1052</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=164&amp;p=1052#p1052"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[illegal opcodes?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=164&amp;p=1052#p1052"><![CDATA[
The only undocummented opcodes being executed were found in a few asian pirate carts, such as "Donkey Kong Country" (well, double-NOPs to be precise) and in an original japanese title too. Invalid opcodes help to detect bad dumps and/or bugs in an emulator. So, I can't see a reason to get all them emulated, unless an original game requires it (as said before). <br /><br />Like Matt said, they are all there, but it doesn't mean your emu will be f*cking accurate... perhaps the oppositive side. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /> Heh, once an UO is executed, something weird might happen.<br /><br />Well, the idea is - emulate when required by a game.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=39">Zepper</a> — Tue Feb 01, 2005 6:12 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
